WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.520
Hello and welcome back. In this new section, we are going to study .NET assemblies and how

00:00:05.520 --> 00:00:12.000
to reverse engineer them using MCP servers connected to dnspy. So first, we take a look

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:20.960
at the evolution of .NET from framework to unified platform. The .NET framework era starts from 2002

00:00:20.960 --> 00:00:28.000
and lasts up to 2019. The original .NET framework was Microsoft's first implementation

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:34.880
designed exclusively for Windows. Versions range from 1 to 4.8, with each release adding new

00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:40.080
features but maintaining Windows-only compatibility. Applications built on .NET

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:45.360
Framework are tied to the specific version installed on the target machine. So initially,

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:50.000
.NET Framework was only for Windows, does not run on Linux or Mac.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:59.880
Then came the .NET Core . Microsoft created .NET Core as a complete rewrite

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:05.620
to address the framework's limitations. This version was cross-platform. It runs on

00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:12.760
Windows, Mac OS, Linux. It is open-source and modular. .NET Core went through versions

00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:22.860
from 1.0 to 3.1. Then came .NET 5 Plus from 2020 to present. Starting with .NET 5, Microsoft unified

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:30.200
the ecosystem under a single .NET brand, dropping Core from the name. So now, you won't see .NET

00:01:30.200 --> 00:01:37.860
Core, you will just see .NET. So .NET is the modern version of the .NET platform. This represents

00:01:37.860 --> 00:01:44.420
the convergence of .NET Framework and .NET Core into one platform. The versioning jumped from .NET

00:01:44.420 --> 00:01:52.980
Core 3.1 directly to .NET 5 to avoid confusion with .NET Framework 4.x. So the last .NET

00:01:52.980 --> 00:02:01.060
Framework was 4.8 and the last .NET Core was 3.1 and the latest .NET is 10. So let's take a look

00:02:01.060 --> 00:02:08.580
at some differences. The key differences are as follows: Platform support: dotnet framework is

00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:17.060
windows only while dotnet core or dotnet 5 plus runs everywhere. Performance. dotnet core and later

00:02:17.060 --> 00:02:23.460
versions are significantly faster and more memory efficient. For deployment, dotnet framework requires

00:02:23.460 --> 00:02:28.740
a runtime to be pre-installed on the target machine while dotnet supports self-contained

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:34.980
deployments that include runtime but most of the time we will require the end user to install the

00:02:34.980 --> 00:02:40.900
dotnet desktop runtime one time and then it can run all the dotnet applications from there on

00:02:40.900 --> 00:02:48.100
if you were to make it self-contained the binary would be too big. Open source: dotnet framework is

00:02:48.100 --> 00:02:56.580
proprietary while dotnet core or dotnet 5 plus is open source and community driven evolution timeline

00:02:56.580 --> 00:03:03.580
The evolution reflects Microsoft's shift from Windows-centric to cloud-first cross-platform development.

00:03:03.580 --> 00:03:08.580
However, there are still some older .NET framework binaries lying around,

00:03:08.580 --> 00:03:12.580
